                                                                  1731 1451
Our resonance parameter evaluation is described below.   File 3   1731 1451
total [MT 1], elastic [MT 2], and capture [MT 102] cross section  1731 1451
values for T=0K for  were computed from the resonance parameter   1731 1451
representation.   For the energy range 0.00001 eV to 1.2 MeV, the 1731 1451
pointwise File 3 cross sections are based on the resonance        1731 1451
parameter files.  Above 1.2 MeV, the current (February 2000) ENDF 1731 1451
cross sections are used.  The CL35 file also contains (n,p) [MT   1731 1451
103,600] cross sections for T = 0K.  For the energy range 0.00001 1731 1451
eV to 121 keV, the pointwise cross sections are based on the      1731 1451
resonance parameter file.   Above 121 keV, the current (February  1731 1451
2000) ENDF cross sections are used.   The last resonance with     1731 1451
non-zero proton width is at 103.5 keV.                            1731 1451
                                                                  1731 1451
We performed an evaluation [1] of Cl neutron cross sections in    1731 1451
the resolved resonance region with the multilevel Reich-Moore     1731 1451
R-matrix formalism. Resonance analyses were carried out with the  1731 1451
computer code SAMMY [3], which utilizes Bayes' method, a          1731 1451
generalized least squares technique.  A recent modification of    1731 1451
SAMMY enabled us to calculate charged particle penetrabilities    1731 1451
for the proton exit channel.  Our evaluation takes advantage of   1731 1451
recent high-resolution capture and transmission measurements at   1731 1451
the Oak Ridge Electron Linear Accelerator (ORELA) to extend the   1731 1451
resolved resonance energy range to 1.2 MeV with much more         1731 1451
accurate representation of the data than previous evaluations.    1731 1451
                                                                  1731 1451
The total cross section data include measurements by Guber, et    1731 1451
al. [2] and Good, et al. [4], on the 80-m flight path at ORELA;   1731 1451
Cierjacks, et al. [5], on a 57-m flight path at the Karlsruhe     1731 1451
Isochronous Cyclotron; Singh, et al. [6] on the 200-m flight      1731 1451
path at the Columbia synchrocyclotron; Brugger, et al. [7], who   1731 1451
utilized a crystal spectrometer and also the MTR fast chopper     1731 1451
with a flight path of 45 m; Kiehn, et al. [8], with the           1731 1451
Rockefeller generator; and Newson, et al. [9], at the Duke Van    1731 1451
de Graaff facility.                                               1731 1451
                                                                  1731 1451
Also included in the evaluation were the high resolution capture  1731 1451
cross section data (0.1 < En < 500 keV) of Guber, et al. [2] and  1731 1451
the older, low resolution capture data (0.02 < En < 1.0 keV) of   1731 1451
Kashukeev, et al. [10]. The 35Cl(n,p)35S cross section data of    1731 1451
Koehler [11] and Druyts, et al. [12] were also fit. The proton    1731 1451
widths are significant fractions of the total widths for          1731 1451
resonances at 398 and 4251 eV.                                    1731 1451
                                                                  1731 1451
In order to give a proper treatment for charged particles in an   1731 1451
exit channel, an algorithm to calculate charged particle          1731 1451
penetrabilities (CPP) and shifts was incorporated in the SAMMY    1731 1451
code. The methodology for CPP computation has been given          1731 1451
previously [13].  Routines based on the CPP algorithm have been   1731 1451
developed and incorporated in a development version of the        1731 1451
nuclear data processing code NJOY [14] for use in preparing data  1731 1451
for criticality safety benchmark calculations.  The nuclear       1731 1451
radii used for penetrabilities and shifts were computed           1731 1451
according to   R = 1.23A**0.33333 + 0.8 fm, where A is the        1731 1451
nuclide mass. These values were 4.8222 and 4.8974 fm for 35Cl     1731 1451
and 37Cl, respectively. In the SAMMY analysis the radii used to   1731 1451
compute hard sphere phase shifts were allowed to vary, and        1731 1451
different radii were allowed for s- and p-waves.  Final values    1731 1451
for 35Cl were R(L=0,1) = 3.6680, 4.8888 fm; final values for 37Cl 1731 1451
were R(L=0,1) = 3.3651,3.9565 fm.                                 1731 1451
