Capture Cross Section Analysis                                    1731 1451
------------------------------                                    1731 1451
Guber, et al. [2] measured the neutron capture of chlorine up to  1731 1451
500 keV using a natural LiCl sample of thickness 0.09812 atoms/b  1731 1451
and the ORELA capture system, which had been re-engineered [20]   1731 1451
to minimize the amount of structural material surrounding the     1731 1451
sample and detectors. To calculate accurate correction factors    1731 1451
for experimental effects of the neutron capture data, reliable    1731 1451
neutron widths are needed since the sample was fairly thick.      1731 1451
Initial neutron widths were obtained by  fitting the              1731 1451
transmission data; using these newly determined values,           1731 1451
corrections for self-shielding and multiple scattering were       1731 1451
calculated with SAMMY and used to determine capture widths.       1731 1451
Several iterations of fitting the transmission and capture data   1731 1451
were performed to obtain final resonance parameters for 0.1 < En  1731 1451
< 500 keV.   From their resonance parameters, Guber, et al. [2],  1731 1451
calculated average cross sections that were rather different      1731 1451
from ENDF/B-VI. This difference is very likely the result of      1731 1451
underestimated neutron sensitivity in the older measurements as   1731 1451
well as an improved calculation of the weighting function.        1731 1451
                                                                  1731 1451
In nuclides where the (n,gamma) cross section is small, the       1731 1451
direct capture (DC) is often a significant fraction of the cross  1731 1451
section. Guber, et al. [2] describe in detail the DC              1731 1451
calculations they performed for 35Cl and 37Cl using the code      1731 1451
TEDCA [21, 22]. They calculated that the effect of the DC         1731 1451
component was very small for 35Cl where the thermal capture       1731 1451
cross section is 43.6 b. However, for 37Cl approximately 0.31 b   1731 1451
of the thermal capture cross section of 0.433 b is due to direct  1731 1451
capture. We have deduced a set of resonance parameters,           1731 1451
including the external level parameters, that reproduce the       1731 1451
resonant part of the capture cross section. To this resonant      1731 1451
part, one must add the DC contribution to obtain the overall      1731 1451
capture cross section. The thermal value of the DC cross section  1731 1451
is 0.16 +- 0.05 b for 35Cl and 0.31 +- 0.16 b for 37Cl.           1731 1451
