SUMMARY AND CONCLUSIONS                                           1731 1451
-----------------------                                           1731 1451
The Cl data used in this evaluation include recent ORELA          1731 1451
high-resolution capture and transmission measurements as well as  1731 1451
several older data sets. Since the 35Cl(n,p)35S reaction yields   1731 1451
a significant contribution to the total cross section from        1731 1451
thermal energies up to about 10 keV, the 35Cl(n,p) data of        1731 1451
Koehler [11] and Druyts, et al. [12] were fit to obtain proton    1731 1451
width values for several resonances. The proton widths are        1731 1451
significant fractions of the total widths for resonances at 398   1731 1451
and 4251 eV. When uncertainties are considered, there is good     1731 1451
agreement between our resonance parameter calculations and        1731 1451
experiment for natCl total cross sections up to 1200 keV, for     1731 1451
35Cl(n,p) cross sections up to 100 keV, and for natCl capture     1731 1451
cross sections up to 500 keV. Our thermal elastic, capture,       1731 1451
(n,p), and total cross sections are in good agreement with the    1731 1451
corresponding ENDF/B-VI quantities, which are based primarily on  1731 1451
the compilation of Mughabghab [15].                               1731 1451
                                                                  1731 1451
Our evaluation fits the data much better than does ENDF/B-VI.     1731 1451
This new representation should be particularly applicable to      1731 1451
improvement of the reliability of criticality safety              1731 1451
calculations for systems where Cl is present.                     1731 1451
                                                                  1731 1451
The present ENDF format does not allow for a resonance parameter  1731 1451
representation of charged particle cross sections. A proposal is  1731 1451
in preparation for a new ENDF format which will permit the full   1731 1451
generality of the Reich-Moore theory, including charged particle  1731 1451
penetrabilities.   The parametric representation (File 2) will be 1731 1451
made available when the new ENDF format is approved.              1731 1451
