SUMMARY                                                           1731 1451
   This evaluation is based primarily on a theoretical analysis   1731 1451
between neutron energies of 100 keV and 20 MeV that is optimized  1731 1451
to the somewhat limited available experimental data.  Elastic     1731 1451
and inelastic scattering angular distributions (through MT=76)    1731 1451
and the radiative capture cross section (MF=3, MT=102)            1731 1451
are taken from the JENDL3.2 evaluation [Wa94].                    1731 1451
   The theoretical calculations utilize Hauser-Feshbach           1731 1451
statistical theory with corrections for width fluctuations,       1731 1451
preequilibrium and direct reaction processes.  Spherical optical  1731 1451
model calculations are used to obtain the neutron total cross     1731 1451
section and neutron, proton, deuteron, triton, and alpha          1731 1451
transmission coefficients.                                        1731 1451
   Cross sections and spectra for individual reactions are        1731 1451
included for exiting neutron, proton, deuteron, alpha, and        1731 1451
gamma-ray reactions.  Multiplicities, angular distributions, and  1731 1451
emission energy spectra are given for gamma rays, particles, and  1731 1451
recoil nuclei emitted in the dominant reactions, utilizing File   1731 1451
6 of the ENDF/B-6 format [Ro91].  Energy-angle-correlated         1731 1451
spectra are given for all outgoing particles and photons, and     1731 1451
residual nuclei energy distributions are included.                1731 1451
